What the hell is this ?

Well, I thought of writing Machine Learning blogs, like everybody else. Scouring the internet gave lot of introductory blogs for introducing Machine learning, Deep Learning, etc. Well, those blogs are definitely great, but while learning deep learning, I started off good. Then I tried Kaggle Competitions, Real world projects, but very soon I found there is a gap in those problems and stuff I learnt on courses, introductory blogs, etc.

Fast foward to present, I decided to help myself on the past. I hope that this series of blog posts, will help to bridge the intermediate void in learning deep learning in a fun way. So let's get started...

Lets begin...

So lets begin with training a Image classifier with Keras and Tensorflow for the sake of those who might need a refresher (like me :') ).

I can thank Jeremy Howard for many things, but today I thank him for his Imagenette Dataset(Read it with french accent XD)

These images are the subset of the famous Imagenet dataset. It consist of 10 easily distinguisable classes. Lets start with something thats close to real life than doing regular MNIST (because MNIST has been done too many times)

Let's peek at one of the images of dataset...

from PIL import Image
img = Image.open('/content/data/imagenette2/train/n01440764/ILSVRC2012_val_00000293.JPEG')
print(img.size)
img

(500, 375)

Big fish isn't it? I believe its 'tench' the infamous first class at Imagenet dataset.

Loading our big guns...

Consider the 9.6k images we downloaded as bullets, and our model is a gun. In order to shoot a bullet from a gun, first you need to load it into a magazine and that magazine needs to be loaded into the gun. Similarly, first you need to divide the images into batches, and each batch is iteratively fed into the model. Considering 9.6k images and the need to be load them into batches of size 32 is definitely a daunting task. So we'll call for help...

tf.Dataset object is our friend here. It iteratively returns images of given batchsize. To convert images into tf.Dataset we can use image_dataset_from_directory from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing

train_path = '/content/data/imagenette2/train'
val_path = '/content/data/imagenette2/val'
train_data = image_dataset_from_directory(train_path,labels='inferred',label_mode='categorical')
val_data = image_dataset_from_directory(val_path,labels='inferred',label_mode='categorical')

Found 9469 files belonging to 10 classes.
Found 3925 files belonging to 10 classes.

Note: The image_dataset_from_directory automatically extracts the class labels from the folder names if the data is present in the format mentioned above.

Note: The default batch size is 32 and default image size is (256,256). You can read more about image_dataset_from_directory here

Wonderful, now let's look at the images, that are reshaped to (256,256) and converted into tf.tensors. Tensors are same as np.ndarrays but we can do GPU computations in it.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

class_names = train_data.class_names

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
for images, labels in train_data.take(1):
  for i in range(9):
    ax = plt.subplot(3, 3, i + 1)
    plt.imshow(images[i].numpy().astype("uint8"))
    plt.title(class_names[i])
    plt.axis("off")

Since we have loaded the images, we now move on to the most exciting part...

Building Models...

It is the most exciting part. To begin with, we'll build a naive, fully connected neural network. A fully connected neural network is a neural network in which every unit is connected with every other unit in the next immediate layer. It is the most primitive of the neural networks, but performs reasonably well. You can read more about fully connected network, here

We will use keras.models.Sequential api to add layers of network one by one.

model = keras.models.Sequential()


model.add(keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(256,256,3)))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu'))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(512,activation='relu'))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(256,activation='relu'))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(10,activation='softmax'))

Note: The first layer is Flatten layer. Fully connected networks accept only a single dimensional input. Since all the color images are 3 dimensional (x, y and 3 RGB channels), we can’t directly pass images directly into fully connected network. Thats why we have to flatten the images using Flatten layer and convert it to single diemsion

Note: The keras.layers.Dense is name for fully connected layer in keras.

As building the model is done, we'll compile the model by defining the loss function and optimizer. Loss is the difference between the predictions of the neural network and actual target. Initially loss is high, as the model weights are random. Then there comes our protogonist optimizer. Optimizer is the heart of any machine learning model, that passes the input images to the model and gets the prediction (forward pass), calculates loss, computes gradients of Loss with respect to every weights and adjusts the weights accordingly (backward pass) for next forward pass. We'll see more about optimizers in forth coming blog posts. For now, we'll use Adam which is a defacto optimizer

model.compile(optimizer='Adam',loss=keras.losses.CategoricalCrossentropy(),metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

Convolutional Neural Network

Convolutional Neural Networks are neural networks that replaces matrix multiplication with mathematical operation called convolution. Its most suitable for images as this provides translational invariance. You can read more about convolution here.

model2 = keras.models.Sequential([
  keras.layers.experimental.preprocessing.Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=(256, 256, 3)),
  keras.layers.Conv2D(16, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  keras.layers.Conv2D(32, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  keras.layers.Conv2D(64, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  keras.layers.Flatten(),
  keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
  keras.layers.Dense(10,activation='softmax')
])

model2.compile(optimizer='sgd',loss=keras.losses.CategoricalCrossentropy(),metrics=['accuracy','AUC'])

model2.summary()

As you can see, the losses look better now. But we can still do better. Generally the models are trained in millions of images for thousands of hours to get state of the art results. But we don't have that much time or computation power. But don't worry, we'll have our friend Transfer Learning, to our aid, where we get state of the art results withing very few data.
